# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>The Reconquista holds the distinction of being the first BattleMech ever produced by Nueva Castile, a collection of deep periphery worlds that had existed in isolation for centuries before contact with the mysterious Umayyad Caliphate in 2830. Produced by the Asturias Royal BattleMech Yard beginning around 2835, the Reconquista was named as a hopeful symbol of the liberation to come.</p><p>A seventy-five-ton primitive design, the Reconquista was crude by any standard, falling far short of even early Inner Sphere designs. Yet, it fulfilled its critical purpose, giving the Castilians their first indigenous BattleMech capability at a time when every 'Mech on the battlefield mattered.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Reconquista is a slow, heavily compromised design born of desperation rather than refined engineering. Its Fury Turbines 180 internal combustion engine propels the seventy-five-ton chassis to a maximum speed of just 32 kilometers per hour, making it one of the slowest 'Mechs ever fielded. This glacial pace left it highly vulnerable to Umayyad artillery and fast-moving armor formations, which could dictate engagement ranges with impunity. The design mounts no jump jets, further limiting its tactical flexibility on any terrain.</p><p>The Reconquista's armament proved more successful than its mobility. A single autocannon/10 provides its primary striking power, capable of delivering punishing hits at medium range. A ten-tube long-range missile launcher offers indirect fire support, while a single machine gun provides close-range anti-infantry capability. The Iron Hide Heavy armor gives the design respectable protection for a primitive 'Mech, and its seven heat sinks prove adequate for the relatively modest heat output of its ballistic and missile weapons.</p><p>The Reconquista's greatest weakness lay in its components. The ICE engine, myomer bundles, chassis frame, control systems, and software were all plagued by mechanical faults, leading to chronic reliability problems throughout the design's service life. Spare parts shortages only compounded these issues.</p>

deployment:<p>No factory variants of the Reconquista are known to have been produced. The Asturias Royal BattleMech Yard manufactured the design in a single configuration throughout its production run, with the Castilian military prioritizing volume over diversification. The 'Mech's primitive construction and limited industrial base made meaningful variant development impractical during the desperate years of the Umayyad conflict. Any battlefield modifications were likely field expedient in nature rather than formalized production variants.</p>

history:<p>The Reconquista's origin traces to the Umayyad invasion of Nueva Castile in 2830. A single JumpShip carrying armed refugees arrived in the Granada system bearing advanced military technology, including BattleMechs. These invaders, dubbed "Umayyads" by the Castilians after the ancient Islamic empire, quickly conquered several worlds. Their BattleMech superiority proved devastating against the conventional Castilian military, and world after world fell to the technologically superior force.</p><p>The tide began to turn when Castilian forces managed to capture an intact Umayyad BattleMech. Combined with intelligence from Umayyad defectors, Castilian engineers at the Asturias Royal BattleMech Yard reverse-engineered the technology and produced the first Reconquista by approximately 2835. While vastly inferior to the Umayyads' Star League-era machines, the Reconquista gave the Castilians their first 'Mech force. By 2841, Reconquistas deployed in company strength were instrumental in halting the Umayyad advance on Valencia. The design's greatest strategic advantage was that it could be manufactured in sufficient numbers at a time when the Umayyads were unable to replace their own 'Mech losses.</p><p>Over approximately twenty-five years, the Asturias yard produced nearly two battalions of Reconquistas. Despite chronic mechanical failures and the design's many shortcomings, these 'Mechs formed the backbone of the Castilian counteroffensive that gradually liberated occupied worlds. The Umayyads countered by producing knock-off Korvin tanks, which proved effective enough to prevent a total Castilian victory, but the strategic balance had shifted permanently.</p><p>As Castilian industrial capability matured, the Reconquista was eventually phased out in favor of more capable, though still primitive, BattleMech designs. The type largely disappeared from frontline service as Nueva Castile's military technology slowly improved over the following centuries. The long conflict between Nueva Castile and the Umayyad Caliphate ground on until a ceasefire was finally reached after Word of Blake operatives revealed that outside powers had been secretly prolonging the war.</p><p>The Reconquista story did not end there, however. When Clan Goliath Scorpion conquered both Nueva Castile and the Umayyad Caliphate, establishing first the Escorpion Imperio and later the Scorpion Empire, some surviving Reconquistas apparently remained in inventory. By 3152, at least one modified Reconquista was reported serving with the Scorpion Conquistadors, a sign of the rugged simplicity of the design, if not its sophistication.</p>

